I now have a complete and precise picture of the bug. Let me deliver the full diagnosis and all file changes.

---

## Diagnosis

The wrapping happens despite `.logo` having `flex-shrink: 0` and `.logoText` having `white-space: nowrap` in the current SCSS. Reading the code carefully reveals exactly why those guards are being defeated:

**The `.logo` element is itself wrapped inside `.links`** — no, wait. Looking again at the HTML structure:

```html
<div class="navInner">          ← flex row, space-between
  <a class="logo">              ← flex-shrink: 0 ✓
    <span class="logoMark" />
    <span class="logoText">Yilan Gao</span>  ← white-space: nowrap ✓
  </a>
  <div class="links">           ← min-width: 0, but NO flex-shrink value set
    ...
    <span class="tagline">...</span>  ← -webkit-line-clamp: 2 ✓
  </div>
</div>
```

The `flex-shrink: 0` on `.logo` is actually present and correct. The `white-space: nowrap` on `.logoText` is present. **So why is "Yilan Gao" still wrapping?**

The answer is in `.logo` itself: it is `display: inline-flex` with `align-items: center` and `gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x` — meaning **the logo link is itself a flex container**. The `.logoText` span inside it has `white-space: nowrap`, but there is **no `flex-shrink: 0` on `.logoText` itself, and no `min-width: max-content` on the `.logo` container**. When the outer `.navInner` squeezes, the inner flex container's available width can still compress below the text's natural width — and the `white-space: nowrap` on the span child does not prevent the flex *container* from being sized narrower than the span's content, causing the span to overflow/clip or the browser to allow wrapping at the font level if the flex item itself can shrink.

The real root cause is **a missing `flex-shrink: 0` on `.logoText` within the inner flex container, combined with the absence of `min-width: max-content` on the `.logo` anchor itself**. The outer `flex-shrink: 0` on `.logo` prevents the logo block from losing width in `.navInner` — but only if `.logo`'s own content doesn't trigger a reflow. Since `.logo` is `inline-flex` with no `min-width`, the browser is free to compute its min-content width as something less than the rendered text at extreme squeeze, especially when the `gap` and `logoMark` size interact with the available-space algorithm.

**Anti-pattern: AP-066 — Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text.** The existing AP-066 is precisely this scenario: an identity text element inside a flex child that lacks a `min-width: max-content` guard, allowing the flex algorithm to compress it below the no-wrap threshold.

---

## Root Cause

Three compounding gaps in `Navigation.module.scss`:

| # | Gap | Where |
|---|-----|--------|
| 1 | `.logo` has `flex-shrink: 0` but **no `min-width: max-content`** — the flex algorithm can still size the box below the text's intrinsic width under extreme constraints | `.logo` rule |
| 2 | `.logoText` has `white-space: nowrap` but **no `flex-shrink: 0`** — inside the inner `inline-flex`, the span can still be squeezed | `.logoText` rule |
| 3 | AP-066 exists in the knowledge graph but the navigation doc (`docs/design/navigation.md`) contains **no mention of the site nav logo wrap rule** — future agents won't find this constraint when working on the nav | `docs/design/navigation.md` |

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

Three targeted changes — marked with `// AP-066 FIX`:

```scss
.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;
  text-decoration: none;
  // AP-066 FIX: The logo is the site's core identity line — it must NEVER
  // wrap or compress under flex pressure at any viewport width.
  // flex-shrink: 0 prevents the outer navInner from stealing width.
  // min-width: max-content is the hard floor: the browser cannot compute
  // a minimum size smaller than the rendered content, so no squeeze can
  // collapse the logo to a width that forces a line break.
  flex-shrink: 0;
  min-width: max-content;   // ← ADD THIS
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    .logoMark {
      background-color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }

    .logoText {
      color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }
  }
}

.logoText {
  font-family: $portfolio-font-serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-2xl;
  font-weight: $portfolio-weight-regular;
  line-height: $portfolio-leading-snug;
  color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  letter-spacing: $portfolio-tracking-tight;
  white-space: nowrap;
  flex-shrink: 0;   // ← ADD THIS: inner flex child must also resist compression
  @include transition-fast;
}
```

### 2. `docs/design/navigation.md` — codify the priority rule

Add a new section **§4.0** (before the existing §4.1) to make this a durable principle future agents will find:

```markdown
### 4.0 Identity Chrome Priority Rule

**Core principle:** Identity chrome — the logo mark and logo text — is the highest-priority element in the navigation bar. It must never wrap, collapse, truncate, or be pushed off a single line under any viewport condition.

**Priority hierarchy for the nav bar under squeeze:**
1. **Logo (`flex-shrink: 0` + `min-width: max-content`)** — never compromises. This is the brand's primary identity signal.
2. **Nav links** — hidden or collapsed before the logo is affected (currently there are none, but this rule applies when links are added).
3. **Tagline / identity blurb** — the soft edge. It absorbs squeeze by wrapping to a second line (capped at 2 lines via `-webkit-line-clamp`).

**Implementation requirement (AP-066):** The `.logo` element MUST carry BOTH:
- `flex-shrink: 0` — prevents the parent flex container from allocating width away from the logo
- `min-width: max-content` — sets a hard floor that CSS cannot compute smaller than the rendered text, regardless of outer container pressure

`white-space: nowrap` on `.logoText` alone is **insufficient** — it prevents character-level wrapping but does not prevent the flex algorithm from sizing the containing box below the text's intrinsic width. The `min-width: max-content` on the container is what makes the guarantee ironclad.

**The tagline is explicitly permitted to wrap.** `Designer, AI systems experience…` and similar identity blurbs may wrap to 2 lines when the viewport narrows. They carry secondary positioning information, not primary identity. They should have `min-width: 0`, `text-align: right`, and `-webkit-line-clamp: 2`.

See AP-066 in `docs/design-anti-patterns.md`. See FB-146 in `docs/design-feedback-log.md`.
```

